segments.text: The Navy Marine Corps winning the Corps.
We had to make not only office space available to them, but decide which of the Corps outfits would be oriented as a Navy Marine outfit as opposed to Army and Air Force.
And I had been thinking about it and trying to pull it out, Don Johnson and I.
And anyway, I put on the list E-2 to the Navy Marines.
And I'll have to admit to this day, I would have never in my life done that if somebody had said, hey, that's Reveille outfit.
It never crossed my mind because I would have never given Reveille to anybody but an Army unit.
I had that much Army in my blood.
So I gave the Navy Marines Reveille.
And there she sits.
With what company had Reveley been before that?
It wasn't E2.
Oh, so it was the designation of E2.
I just designated E2 would be one of the companies that they can take responsibility for.
And, you know, it still had Army and Air Force.
We were all mismatched up.
If a cadet wanted to be in an Army-oriented outfit, it didn't matter whether he had a contract or he was in Air Force or whatever.
So they could go to any outfit they wanted to, and we didn't tell them they had to be in that program.
Alright, as the Navy and Marine Corps began here, General Simpson soon came, were there then some Navy and Marine Corps officers also detached, assigned here?
Oh yeah, they opened up a big detachment there, Colonel
He just passed away over in the grad school.
We'll think of it later.
Who were the, how easy was it for the rest of the Corps to accept this addition?
The Corps didn't have any problem with it.
Is that right?
Yeah.
So that went well.
Yeah, they were just happy to say, you know, more.
The Marines, the Navy Marines program, they brought in a heck of a lot of,
scholarship signals from, you know, and they'd take them all over the United States and they'd tell them where to go.
And they brought them in here.
So there were no problems with that at all?
No, not with the Corps.
It was totally a service oriented thing of protecting your service sort of stuff.
Now, and when you arrived, were there already some black Corps members?
I don't think so.
I don't remember any.
Alright, during your years, there were some black members of the Corps.
There were one or two showing up.
There were not many.
Did you ever encounter any hazing problems related to race?
Were there any problems in the Corps?
I didn't know anything that was, you know, nobody saying, you dirty Mexican or anything.
Never.
I've never heard of any.
Never.
Everybody, if you're in the Corps, you're a Corps.
And it's still that way now.
Women in the Corps and men in the Corps, there was a lot of problems with that.
But I still think most of them accept it and agree with it and it seems to me that they're treated pretty good.
All right.
While you were Commandant, were there women in the Corps?
That's me again.
I was, yes, I was.
Please describe.
I was pressured the year before we started the program by the Army.
And Crossland was being pressured by the Air Force saying, we want women in the program, in the ROTC.
You can have them in the ROTC.
They don't have to be in the Corps.
Well, we don't want anybody in the ROTC who wasn't in the Corps.
Well, the Army called me one day and said, great news for you.
You're going to be the test unit in the Fourth Army for women.
And we're going to start you out this fall.
And I said, no, sir.
We're not going to start now this fall.
The university has not accepted that program.
And so they went to San Antonio to... St. Mary's?
No, the Trinity.
Trinity?
And that's where they were the first in the state of Texas.
So I called, I talked to Dr. Williams too about this.
And Dr. Williams and I met one day and he says,
You know, the pressure is on everybody on this thing, and I know it's on you, and they said, I think it's time we took the move, don't you?
And I said, yes, sir.
It's getting real tough for the Army for me.
I mean, they were really putting the screws on me, and they were in a position to do it.
And so were the former students, but we took a big hassle from former students, and I had many of my classmates call me and were not too happy with me.
What was their basic argument against?
They just didn't want women in the Corps.
What do they think would be?
I don't think there was any logic to it whatsoever.
Even with the guys in the Corps at that time, they didn't want those females over there, although they all had girlfriends and this, that, and the other.
You know, they hadn't recognized that women played a big part in it.
And they were playing a big part in the military when I was, you know, on active duty elsewhere.
And they did a lot of jobs.
They did well and better than the men.
But it was not an easy task, so that was one of the real problems I was working with.
When did the women first enter the Corps, do you remember?
Seventy-two.
Seventy-two.
And about how many were there that year?
About thirty.
And Ruth Ann Schumacher was the first to become a company.
The first year they had a male company commander.
Ruth Ann was the first.
female commander and did a marvelous job.
Her brother was in the Corps, and her father was a colonel, and she went in the service, so she was the first female officer commissioned into the regular Army through an ROTC program.
Nationally?
In a military program.
Nationally.
I'm sorry?
You're saying nationally, not just for A&M, but nationally.
Oh, right.
We did it before West Point, VMI, I said it.
We were the first military school to integrate women.
What were some of the problems that you, as the Commandant, had to cope with about women in the Corps?
Well, it was mostly with my former students.
I didn't have too much trouble with the Corps.
They didn't like it.
But I flat-told them, this is going to happen.
And I want to know from you how you give me a plan of integration, which I did.
They called it the Miranda Plan.
And they got us a war.
They did a whole lot better job than I could have done.
And, of course, we were struggling around figuring out how we were going to do this, that, and the other.
But most of the guidance came from the core of how they would do it.
And I disagreed with some of them.
For example, they said there would never be in pinks and greens.
Never be in boots.
I said, well, we're not talking that now, and so forth.
Well, anyway, we got it going in the first year they didn't have uniforms.
They didn't have them because we didn't know how many we were going to have, and one thing or another, this was a, believe me, it was a big problem.
But we got around that thing and the girls, one of them came over to me one day and said, we need some recognition.
Said, could we at least have name tags?
And I said, you bet.
I'll have them tomorrow and give me a list.
And so we got those.
And so that was the only identification they had.
And they didn't live in the dorm that year because we didn't know how many dorm spaces.
But they had to come out and do the breakfast mccall and all that stuff.
But the second year is when we went into the uniform business.
And the girls themselves pretty much designed, they wanted to do the A-line skirts.
And I didn't know what an A-line from a B-line was and all that sort of stuff.
And the people over at the warehouse over there did a fantastic job.
They had their own company that second year?
They had, they were still, the entire time I was there, they were not integrated into the W-1, and we selected that W for women.
And it was Army?
Well, Army was supervised.
But it was, they could be in any branch, any of the three branches?
Oh yes, any ROTC program they wanted to be in.
And they were pretty well evened out, Army and Air Force, later on Navy.
But we did put them over in the dorm too.
And we got the university to renovate it to put in privacy stalls.
And strangely enough, they didn't like that.
Took the urinals out and all that.
That baffled me.
I'd have liked to have them when I was a cadet to have a little privacy.
They wanted the same thing as the guys did.
And after I left, they moved them in their regular dormitory.
But, you know, it's hard to understand for me.
But anyway, after their second year, it's coming up time to be pinks and greens.
Well, of course, they have no pinks and greens.
Well, Nancy Hart, who I commissioned later, came in that summer and we talked about it.
And I said, Nancy, you got a lot of gumption, I think.
And she said, yes, sir.
And I said, well, we're going to put you in green
shirt and pink skirt.
And, uh, can you handle it?
She said, oh, yes, sir, you bet.
And she showed up in that thing and there was some hassle, but it was accepted.
And that's, uh, that was the start of giving them those privileges.
Uh, I never considered boats, uh, and I don't like them now.
I just don't think it looks good, but that's, there'll be no small.
But, uh, anyway, the, uh,
The clothing people, they really did a fantastic job because we had no idea, and I certainly had none.
And I had a real problem looking after the girls because I couldn't really go into the dorms.
And I guess some of the male guys did, I don't know, but I would never go in without a female accompanying me.
But I told the Army, I said, okay, you want me to do this program, you get me a woman officer.
And they had a tough time getting me one and it hurt me, but they did.
I got one pretty fast, a young lieutenant named Holtzman.
What?
H-O-L-T-Z-M-A-N, Teresa Holtzman.
Teresa Holtzman.
She was a Yankee girl, went to college in the North and talked like one.

and she was just as sweet as she could be, and I'm not saying that in a male-female situation, but she really worked with those gals, and she brought them a long way, and I think they cared a lot about her, and she just did a fabulous job, and maybe later on brought one in too, but boy, we needed them bad, and they'd come to me with the,

or this A-line skirt on it, and they were wearing these short things anyway, and one of them come in one day in my office, they'd come in a lot of times to talk, and sitting there, I finally just had to say, I know her name, I'd say, look, I don't want to see the color of your underwear.
Would you please pull your skirt down?
Now, that's pretty embarrassing to have to do, and we laughed about it later, and I did, but I didn't want to embarrass her, but
But anyway, Theresa was able to do the little things, but they were big things for me.
It was hard for a man to handle.
What kind of pranks did the male corps members attempt on the females?
They gave them a lot of hassle.
I don't know everything, but I do know I got a call one time that the company C2, who were then at that time in Dorm 3,
was mooning the girls over in dorm two, and they were mooning them back.
And I had to get into the moon fight, but that was pretty easy to settle.
In the dining halls, when they'd have a food fight, did they ever throw stuff at the girls?
I'm not aware of any of that.
I'm not even aware of food fights in the dining hall where I had to knock it at girls.
Oh, really?
Oh, OK.
I don't know whether I had them or not.
Good.
And out on the drill field, did they ever do anything to harass the females?
Not to my knowledge, but I'm sure they gave them a hard time.
I mean, as long as they were in a room unit, they leaned on each other.
And I did not integrate them into the male units, so that was done after my time.
I was not named in the lawsuit either.
I don't know why, but maybe because I was the one that was trying to push a program.
And poor old Jim Woodall got the hassle of it because that was the time I retired.
But I got along with them well, and my wife and I attended their out-of-date functions when they invited us.
And they were living in, most of them in one of these dorm complexes off campus.
And they had a party over there one time and I went to it.
They asked my wife, would the colonel get real mad if we took him to the quad in the swimming pool?
And she said, no, if you just tell him so he can get his boots off and all that stuff.
So they carried me and dumped me in there.
The girls did?
Yes.
And they did the same thing the guys do, because on the way to that swimming pool, after I got out, I told my wife they can take me again, because they unzipped my pants and somebody reached in.
I said, let them take me again.
And she said, what part?
She said, no way.
So they got the spirit pretty fast, I guess.
I don't know who it was.
I communicate with two or three of them.
Robin Gibson, General Gibson was her father.
He was an Ivy II star then.
Now she's married to one of the guys who was on the Corps staff.
She's a lieutenant colonel in the reserve now.
She's sitting on after duty as well.
Her husband is going to become a general pretty soon, I think, pretty quickly.
She was a big talker.
She was just an inspiration.
Looking back on coeducation in the Corps, what did we do well and what could we have done better?
I don't know how we would have gotten it done easier.
It would have been better, I suppose, if we'd had a female officer in the beginning.
It took several months to get one down here, a female active officer, because the Corps males, you know, would quote the commander and this, that, and the other.
I don't really know what went on over there.
I never went into the dorm after it was occupied.
And I did, you know, there were other girls over there, they didn't fill up the dormitory, and a lot of them asked for that dorm for some reason.
I don't know whether they just wanted to be in a core dorm, core type, and they were cheaper than they were then.
You're saying civilian girls.
Right, right.
And I did from time to time get phone calls from,
from the parents of those girls.
You know, every once in a while somebody's parents can't get in touch with them.
And you know, as well as I do, usually they're out with somebody else and so forth, which I knew about.

And this one parent was so devastated, and something has happened to his daughter, and I finally, you know, I was going to tell him, I finally said, I'm a father, and I have a daughter, and you have a right to know, too, that she's okay.
She's just not in her own room.
That's what happens.
I mean, you can't do much about that.
But I'm glad to have been there in that part of A&M's history.
I'm sorry for half of the cause, but
And looking back on it, it wasn't all that bad, but it was a mean time.
Let's see, secret fraternities and so forth.
I never, you're asking, I knew nothing about anything.
And there was no investigation during your time about that?
No.
Okay.
Other than Bob Melcher, I don't know what he was doing, but he asked me questions sort of like that.
I just, I never knew anything like that.
Because I think after that there was a, after your...
I think there might have been some under Woodall because I do have one of those little mimeographed letters that they put out, but I don't know whether that was organized or not.
And Jim Woodall took one of the
whatever happened, I imagine, and he was a good man.
He was a good man.
I'm sorry I had to leave him with those problems, but the time came when the Army told me to leave.
When you were Commandant, what was it like to be responsible for a Corps trip?
Well, it wasn't any problem.

Usually Jerry Maynard, the university employee, sent him up ahead of time to make arrangements with the police and all those people and tell them how to get a hold of him in case one of the guys was in trouble or got hurt or anything else.
So we manned a phone and told the Corps, you know, if you need somebody, call this phone.
The military people were required
to go on these court trips just for the game, I mean for the marching band.
We had no money to pay them.
The Army would not give me per diem money.
The Navy had it.
They could pay their people.
All I could get were the free football, two free football game tickets and we'd give them $10 apiece.
We had no trouble filling it because I say most of the officers were Aggies.
And they would have probably paid us to go.
And at least I never had any trouble filling up the Army officer.
And my responsibility in those things was primarily, again, taking care of the reviewing officer, particularly Dr. Williams, which usually wasn't too much of a problem.
But one year I didn't know he was going to fly up there in the old airport love field.
And that the university didn't send a car, and I got a call from the elder, could I pick him up?
And I said, yeah, I'll pick him up when we get in.
Well, I was in my Vega, and that's all I had.
I wasn't in my pickup.
And he wasn't too charmed with riding in my Vega, and he told me, he said, don't ever pick me up in my little car like this again.
And I said, yes, sir.
And from then on, I'd had a university vehicle with me.
Now, did you go to just about every Corps trip?
Oh, yeah.
Of all the four places where the Corps went on those trips, which ones were the most pleasant and which ones were the most difficult?
Well, Austin, obviously, was always difficult.
Is that right?
Yes.
Describe it.
Well, half of the kids and the other hundreds or whatever, I don't know what I want to call them,
And they'd boo them and so forth.
But Dallas-Fort Worth, man, the bag is all the way up there.
Houston?
Houston was always great.
That was, during my time, that was organized by old Harris, George Harris, moving stories.
George was a big benefactor of the university.
And he always got the review and stand, got the clearance and paid the thousand dollars that we had to pay the city and all that kind of stuff.
But Houston, they liked the Aggies too.
We'll have about a half or more Aggies in Houston anyway.
And the local authorities cooperated?
Yes, we never, never had any.
They liked the Aggies too.
The policemen liked the Aggies because of the uniform and all that stuff.
To me, there's very little difference between the mentality of police and military anyway.
Maybe the military officers might be a little better educated, but they still have the same mentality.
Do you remember any other out-of-town football games during your commandant years that you went to?
Well, I remember there was a rice game when Dr. Vandiver did his thing.
I thought we were going to have a real, real problem.
And I was in the stands, and I had a general officer with me, and I was in the uniform.

But what really started it was these guys from Rice come out with T-shirts where they printed, fuck me, and I'm going to pardon the language in there, but that's what it said, which was very offensive, not to me as an Aggie, but to me as a person.
And then they'd blow in the whistle, and the band march,
They were wearing German helmets and had swastikas.
I'm just amazed that they didn't go out of those things.
Now, you were then campus security.
You weren't commandant.
I was commandant then.
Oh, really?
Because that's AD...
When I was coming out, no, it wasn't, it was 70...
It might have been that, I might have had my years wrong.
Oh, it was Jarvis Miller.
Yeah, yeah.
Wasn't Vandiver.
Vandiver's the one who directed the Rice Band that time.
That's right, that's right.
I got my stories wrong.
And if I'm not mistaken, after the game was over, didn't some of us have to kind of go and help keep Aggies away from the Rice Band?
Right, that did happen.
Yeah.
What about, were there any trips to, say, to West Point or any other out-of-town big games along the way that you remember?
We didn't...
Well, the kids didn't go to these games too much back then.
The band couldn't go to too many of them.
It was a financial thing.

And I never really went to any other than the Corps trip games and maybe the Baylor game and one time to Lubbock when Don Johnson was still on flight pay and he'd do a cross country and we'd go in an Army aircraft.
And incidentally, Don was probably the smartest thing I ever did as Commandant.
He was already, you know, there under McCoy and he was working in the office and he worked for me a little while, a couple of years, and then he was transferred still on active duty.
And he was transferred to an Army medical board in Pennsylvania and they dissolved the board.
And we were talking on the phone one day, and I said, where are you going now, Don?
They said, I don't know.
I said, would you like to come back down here?
Yeah, but they never met me.
And I said, well, I don't know whether or not, but if you want to come back, let me give it a try.
Well, I really knew a lot of people.
You know, when you go through the Army War College, you make contact.
And I knew quite a few people in the Pentagon.
And I started calling around.
Lo and behold, he called me one day and said, hey, I got orders.
Come there now.
So anyway, we got him back down.
Then when he was a reserve officer, so he had to retire after 20.
And I said, do you want to stay on?
I'll see if I can get a position.
And so I was able to get that position for him.
And what position did you?
The one he's in right now, assistant to the commandant.
Yeah.
And what were the duties of the assistant to the commandant, in fact?
All the dirty jobs, disciplinary program
Most of the coordination of core activities and that sort of stuff, just about anything you can think of Don did.
And he's well deserving of the recognition that he has.
He's a fantastic person.
And I think these are the glue that has held that office together.
Describe how Parsons Mounted Cavalry came about.
Oh, that's right.
Let's see.
Well, let's see.
I think this was in 71, no, 72.
Three guys came in to see me and wanted to know if they'd been thinking about mounted units and this, that, and the other and how I feel about it.
I said, well, you know, we used to have them.
It sounded like a pretty good idea.
But I said, well, how would it be?
Do you think we could bring three horses in behind the Corps and one of the marching units?
And I said, let me talk to Corps commander, but I think we can handle that.
And so anyway, they did that.
And the crowd seemed to like it a little bit.
And so then we got together after that was over.
They said, we really want to start this.
What are your thoughts?
And so I said, well, if we do it, I think it should be the same as RVs and everything else and activity oriented.
But I think that it should not be open to company commanders or RVs.
And they said, why?
And I said, because these are already people that are in positions of responsibility and pride and so forth and
all these others are good aggies, too, and let them have another outlet, which happened to be the cow.
It isn't that way now, but that's the way it was originally.
But anyway, I said, what do you need?
And they said, well, we need some seed money.
And I said, how much?
And they said 10,000.
I went over to see Buck Wires.
And I had that money before I walked out of his office.
I mean, he was just overjoyed.
And so Buck, you know, stood behind us and got us going.
Dean Fritz, John Fritz, I'm sure you know him, got wind of it, and he, gosh, what he's done for the cows, nobody can imagine, and money, and whatever.
So you started with three horses.
Three cows, well, the next year, we put them on the field.
How many?
I think 28, 30, something like that load.
And they were their own horses?
They had to have access to their own horse.
It had to be a bale saw.
They had to be able to financially take care of it.
The university allowed us to use a strip of land out of Brownfield and there was an old army shelter there.
Ten acres we could use.
And they worked real hard out there and they were the real
because we were going out and taking care of them.
That's a long way out on the bike, and training and everything else.
I went out there a lot of times, and my wife too.
She loved to ride, and she rode with them out to nowhere else for us.
But we got booted out of there.
The engineer said they had to have that back.
I don't believe it to this day, but they booted us over
what they call a hernia hill which College Station now has a directory and a bunch of aggers owned it and they let them use that for a couple of years and then sold it to College Station.
Then they bumped them out in the woods out there near the green where they are now and close to the arena.
Give us two acres out there fully wooded and said this is all we can do.
And so we started trying to clear it and build a barn and this, that, and the other.
And when I say we, that's physically we and Army officers and some of the other kids that were around.
But meanwhile, we all had moved in and had a good relationship with Dr. Miller.
And he got on a wagon there with Dr. Miller and they went up to,
O.D.
Butler's office and told them they wanted the present location.
You may know this story.
And anyway, O.D.
said, Dr. Miller, we can spare that piece of property from the agriculture department or whatever.
And Dr. Miller said to him, Jim related this to me, that says, O.D., you're a general in the reserve, aren't you?
And he said, yes, I am.
You know that.
And he says, when you get an order from your general boss, what do you do?
And he says, I salute and say, yes, sir, and do it.
And he says, what are you going to do now?
Yes, sir, and salute him.
And we got the land.
And Jim was really, and Dr. Miller was really responsible for that.
And that was a godsend.
I don't think Cal would be around if it wasn't for that.
And what are some of the proudest moments you remember
about the cavalry or the mounted... Well, of course, I was overwhelmed when the...
